Handson2 - Angular Binding Types & Lifecycle Hooks
Task 1: All Four Binding Types
Goal: Practice interpolation, property binding, event binding and two-way binding.

1. In HomeComponent, declare:
portalName = 'Student Course Portal';

Template:
<h1>{{ portalName }}</h1>

2. Property Binding
isPortalActive = true;

<button [disabled]="!isPortalActive">Enroll Now</button>

3. Event Binding
message = '';

onEnrollClick(){
  this.message = 'Enrollment opened!';
}

<button (click)="onEnrollClick()">Enroll Now</button>
<p>{{ message }}</p>

4. Two-Way Binding
Import FormsModule.

searchTerm = '';

<input [(ngModel)]="searchTerm">
<p>Searching for: {{ searchTerm }}</p>

5. Difference
[property] : One-way binding (Component → DOM)
[(ngModel)] : Two-way binding (Component ↔ DOM)

Expected Output:
• Typing updates 'Searching for' instantly.
• Clicking Enroll Now shows 'Enrollment opened!'.
• Button is enabled/disabled using isPortalActive.

Task 2: Lifecycle Hooks
Goal: Implement Angular lifecycle hooks.

1. Implement ngOnInit

export class HomeComponent implements OnInit{

  ngOnInit(){
    console.log('HomeComponent initialised – courses loaded');
  }

}

2. Implement ngOnDestroy

export class HomeComponent implements OnDestroy{

  ngOnDestroy(){
    console.log('HomeComponent destroyed');
  }

}

3. Generate Course Card Component

ng g c components/course-card

4. Implement ngOnChanges

@Input() course:any;

ngOnChanges(changes: SimpleChanges){
 console.log(changes);
}

5. Render three CourseCard components inside CourseListComponent with different hardcoded courses.

Expected Output:
• ngOnInit fires when HomeComponent loads.
• ngOnDestroy fires when leaving the page.
• ngOnChanges logs changes whenever @Input() value changes.

